<DOC><DOCNO> AP890404-0231 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1340EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-India-Carbide     04-04 0248</FIRST><SECOND>BC-India-Carbide,0257</SECOND><HEAD>Bhopal Victims Want Union Carbide Declaration To Court Stopped</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Lawyers of the Bhopal gas leak victimsTuesday cautioned the Supreme Court against accepting a declarationby Union Carbide Corp. concerning compensation money to thevictims, news reports said.   Union Carbide, in an affidavit, said it had complied with thecourt's order to deposit a part of the $470 million compensationfor the victims of the Dec. 2-3, 1984, gas leak, United News ofIndia news agency said.   More than 3,400 people were killed and at least 20,000 injuredwhen deadly methyl isocynate gas spewed from a pesticide plant runby the Indian subsidiary of Union Carbide in the central Indiancity of Bhopal.   Three lawyers, arguing on behalf of some victims, said that oncethe court accepted the declaration, the U.S multinational wouldrefuse to submit to the jurisdiction of the Indian court, UnitedNews of India said.   The five-judge panel will hear arguments Thursday on theobjections by Shanti Bhushan, Soli Sorabji and Indira Jaising.   The panel, headed by Chief Justice R.S. Pathak, on Feb. 14-15ordered Union Carbide to pay $465 million as compensation followinga Feb. 14 settlement between the Indian government and UnionCarbide. The company had earlier give $5 million to the Red Cross.   Union Carbide's attorney told the court that under the terms ofthe settlement the compensation money had been deposited and the``settlement orders stood complied with,'' United News of Indiareported.</TEXT></DOC>